---
import { Card, CardContent, CardDescription, CardHeader, CardTitle } from "@/components/ui/card";
import SiteLayout from "@/layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const lastUpdated = "April 4, 2026";
---

<SiteLayout
  title="Privacy Notice · pkgs.ml"
  description="Privacy notice for pkgs.ml"
>
  <section class="mx-auto w-full max-w-6xl px-4 py-6 sm:px-6">
    <div class="grid gap-4">
      <nav class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 text-sm text-muted-foreground">
        <a href="/" class="hover:text-foreground">All packages</a>
        <span>/</span>
        <span class="text-foreground">privacy</span>
      </nav>

      <Card className="rounded-md shadow-none">
        <CardHeader className="border-b border-border">
          <CardTitle className="text-base">Privacy Notice for pkgs.ml</CardTitle>
          <CardDescription>
            Last updated: {lastUpdated}
          </CardDescription>
        </CardHeader>
        <CardContent className="grid gap-8 py-4 text-base leading-7 text-muted-foreground">
          <section class="grid gap-3">
            <p>
              pkgs.ml is Riot's OCaml package registry. This notice explains what data pkgs.ml
              processes, why it processes that data, and how the service tries to keep that data
              minimal.
            </p>
            <p>
              The service is intentionally designed around data minimization. In practice, that
              means pkgs.ml stores the identity and security data needed to authenticate users,
              operate package publishing, and expose public package metadata, while avoiding
              generic request logging and raw IP-based analytics in the registry database.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-3">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">1. Controller and contact</h2>
            <p>
              The controller for personal data processed through pkgs.ml is the operator of
              pkgs.ml.
            </p>
            <p>
              Privacy questions and requests can be sent to{" "}
              <a class="text-foreground hover:text-primary" href="mailto:privacy@pkgs.ml">
                privacy@pkgs.ml
              </a>.
            </p>
            <p>
              If pkgs.ml is later operated by a legal entity, this notice should be updated to
              name that entity and its contact details explicitly.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-3">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">2. What data pkgs.ml collects</h2>

            <div class="grid gap-2">
              <h3 class="font-medium text-foreground">GitHub account data</h3>
              <p>
                When you sign in with GitHub, pkgs.ml stores your GitHub login, GitHub user ID,
                display name when available, avatar URL, primary email address, and whether that
                primary email address is verified. pkgs.ml currently requires a verified primary
                email address to complete sign-in.
              </p>
              <p>
                pkgs.ml also stores a copy of your GitHub avatar in registry storage so that the
                web UI can continue to display your avatar without depending on a live GitHub API
                request on every page load.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="grid gap-2">
              <h3 class="font-medium text-foreground">Session and authentication data</h3>
              <p>
                pkgs.ml uses a secure session cookie named <code>pkgs_session</code> to keep you
                signed in. In the registry database, pkgs.ml stores the session ID, the user ID it
                belongs to, the associated GitHub login, the session creation time, and the expiry
                time.
              </p>
              <p>
                The session cookie is <code>HttpOnly</code>, <code>Secure</code>, and{" "}
                <code>SameSite=Lax</code>. It is used only for authentication and authenticated
                account actions.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="grid gap-2">
              <h3 class="font-medium text-foreground">Publish token data</h3>
              <p>
                If you create an API publish token, pkgs.ml shows the plaintext token exactly once
                at creation time. After that, pkgs.ml stores only the token ID, a derived hash of
                the secret, the owning user and GitHub login, the token name, capability metadata,
                creation time, last-used time, and revocation time if the token is revoked.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="grid gap-2">
              <h3 class="font-medium text-foreground">Public package and registry data</h3>
              <p>
                pkgs.ml is a public registry. When a package is published, the service stores and
                serves public registry metadata such as package name, version, description,
                license, homepage, repository, categories, keywords, dependencies, owner login,
                public artifact digests, manifests, and public package/source archives.
              </p>
              <p>
                Package ownership information shown on package pages and user pages is public by
                design. Published package artifacts and metadata may also be cached or mirrored as
                part of normal registry operation.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="grid gap-2">
              <h3 class="font-medium text-foreground">Operational events</h3>
              <p>
                pkgs.ml stores purpose-built package lifecycle events rather than generic request
                logs. These events include publication and indexing events such as package
                submission, verification, publication, indexing, and searchability. Event rows
                record the event ID, type, package name, package version, optional package locator,
                a structured payload, and the event timestamp.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="grid gap-2">
              <h3 class="font-medium text-foreground">Analytics data currently collected</h3>
              <p>
                pkgs.ml currently stores only a small number of purpose-built analytics facts for
                aggregate ecosystem statistics:
              </p>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-5">
                <li>package downloads: package name, version, artifact digest, source archive key, and timestamp;</li>
                <li>Riot binary downloads: binary name, object key, and timestamp;</li>
                <li>OCaml toolchain downloads: binary name, object key, and timestamp; and</li>
                <li>index reads: document key, package name when applicable, and timestamp.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These tables are used to produce aggregate registry statistics such as package
                installs, Riot installs, OCaml installs, index refreshes, and package-level
                download counts.
              </p>
            </div>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-3">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">3. Data pkgs.ml does not currently collect by default</h2>
            <p>
              pkgs.ml does not currently treat generic request logging as a product feature, and it
              does not intentionally store raw IP addresses in the registry database for analytics
              or product reporting.
            </p>
            <p>
              pkgs.ml also does not currently store generic page-view logs, unique visitor IDs,
              search query analytics, or advertising and cross-site tracking identifiers in the
              registry database. If a future feature requires new analytics data, the intent is to
              keep that collection narrowly scoped, documented, and anonymous where possible.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-3">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">4. How pkgs.ml collects data</h2>
            <p>pkgs.ml collects data directly from you when you:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-5">
              <li>sign in with GitHub;</li>
              <li>create or revoke publish tokens;</li>
              <li>publish a package artifact; or</li>
              <li>download package artifacts, Riot binaries, OCaml toolchains, or sparse index documents.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              pkgs.ml also receives account information from GitHub during OAuth sign-in and stores
              a small number of registry events and analytics facts automatically as part of
              operating the service.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-3">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">5. Why pkgs.ml processes data</h2>

            <div class="grid gap-2">
              <h3 class="font-medium text-foreground">To authenticate users and manage accounts</h3>
              <p>
                GitHub identity data and session data are used to sign users in, maintain user
                accounts, associate package ownership, and display account identity in the web
                interface.
              </p>
              <p>
                Legal basis: performance of a contract or steps taken at your request before
                providing authenticated registry features.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="grid gap-2">
              <h3 class="font-medium text-foreground">To operate package publication securely</h3>
              <p>
                Publish token metadata, session data, package claims, and publication events are
                used to create, validate, revoke, and audit publish credentials and publishing
                actions.
              </p>
              <p>
                Legal basis: performance of a contract and legitimate interests in keeping the
                registry secure and preventing unauthorized publication.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="grid gap-2">
              <h3 class="font-medium text-foreground">To run the public registry</h3>
              <p>
                Package metadata, ownership metadata, manifests, artifacts, and index documents are
                used to render package pages, user pages, search results, sparse index documents,
                and public downloads.
              </p>
              <p>
                Legal basis: performance of a contract and legitimate interests in operating a
                usable public package ecosystem.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="grid gap-2">
              <h3 class="font-medium text-foreground">To expose aggregate usage statistics</h3>
              <p>
                Purpose-built analytics facts such as download counts and index reads are used to
                produce aggregate statistics pages and to understand service usage without relying
                on generic IP-based request logging.
              </p>
              <p>
                Legal basis: legitimate interests in operating, improving, and securing the
                service.
              </p>
            </div>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-3">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">6. Recipients and infrastructure</h2>
            <p>
              pkgs.ml does not sell personal data. Data may be processed by a limited number of
              infrastructure providers that are needed to run the service.
            </p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-5">
              <li>GitHub, for user authentication;</li>
              <li>Cloudflare, for hosting, storage, sessions, delivery, and registry infrastructure; and</li>
              <li>public users of the registry, but only for data that is public by design, such as published package metadata and ownership information.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              Data may also be disclosed where required by law or where reasonably necessary to
              protect the security, integrity, or operation of the service.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-3">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">7. International transfers</h2>
            <p>
              Because pkgs.ml relies on online infrastructure and GitHub authentication, data may
              be processed outside your country. Where applicable, the operator of pkgs.ml should
              rely on appropriate safeguards for international transfers.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-3">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">8. Retention</h2>
            <p>
              pkgs.ml keeps personal data only for as long as reasonably necessary to provide the
              service, maintain package ownership and publish security, comply with legal
              obligations, and preserve the integrity of the public registry.
            </p>
            <p>
              In practice, that means account, package ownership, token metadata, and publication
              records may remain stored while they are needed to operate the service and maintain a
              coherent public package ecosystem. Published package metadata and package artifacts
              may need to remain available as part of registry continuity even if a user later
              stops using the service.
            </p>
            <p>
              pkgs.ml does not currently publish fixed retention windows for every category of
              operational data. Where a fixed period is not yet defined, retention is based on
              operational need, security, legal obligations, and ecosystem integrity.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-3">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">9. Whether you must provide data</h2>
            <p>
              If you want to use authenticated features such as package management or publish token
              administration, you need to provide the GitHub account data required for sign-in.
              If you want to publish packages with a token, you need to create and use a publish
              token.
            </p>
            <p>
              If you choose not to provide the data needed for authentication or publishing,
              pkgs.ml may be unable to provide those authenticated registry features to you.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-3">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">10. Cookies and similar technologies</h2>
            <p>
              pkgs.ml uses one authentication cookie, <code>pkgs_session</code>, to keep signed-in
              users authenticated. pkgs.ml does not currently describe or use advertising cookies or
              unrelated tracking cookies on its public privacy page.
            </p>
            <p>
              The website also stores the light or dark theme preference in local browser storage
              so the UI can remember your choice. That preference is used only for presentation.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-3">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">11. Your rights</h2>
            <p>
              Subject to applicable law, you may have the right to access your personal data,
              rectify inaccurate personal data, erase personal data, restrict processing, object to
              processing based on legitimate interests, receive the personal data you provided in a
              portable format where applicable, and withdraw consent where processing depends on
              consent.
            </p>
            <p>
              If you make a request, pkgs.ml should respond within the time required by applicable
              law.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-3">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">12. Complaints</h2>
            <p>
              If you are in the EEA, UK, or another jurisdiction with similar rights, you may lodge
              a complaint with your local supervisory authority if you believe your personal data
              has been processed unlawfully or your rights have not been respected.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-3">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">13. Automated decision-making</h2>
            <p>
              pkgs.ml does not currently describe automated decision-making or profiling that
              produces legal or similarly significant effects on users. If that changes, this
              notice should be updated.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="grid gap-3">
            <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-foreground">14. Changes to this notice</h2>
            <p>
              pkgs.ml may update this notice from time to time. If material changes are made, the
              updated version should be published on this page together with an updated "Last
              updated" date.
            </p>
          </section>
        </CardContent>
      </Card>
    </div>
  </section>
</SiteLayout>
